# GENERATED FILE — do not edit kitty/kitty.conf by hand.
# Source template: theme/templates/kitty.conf.in
# Palette:         theme/palettes/<active>.env  (rendered by theme/gen.py)
# kitty reads its config on launch, so a regenerated file applies to NEW kitty
# windows. (kitty can also live-reload the config with ctrl+shift+F5.)
#
# Symlinked into place:  ~/.config/kitty/kitty.conf -> ~/dotfiles/kitty/kitty.conf
#
# kitty is the terminal on real hardware — it needs GPU acceleration the
# VirtualBox VM's software-rendered GPU couldn't serve, which is why the
# workshop ran `foot` instead (see vm-substitutions.md). foot stays installed
# and palette-generated as a fallback.
#
# Purpose (roadmap step 5): make the terminal's background semi-transparent so
# the wallpaper shows through *behind* the text, while the text itself stays
# fully opaque. This is kitty's own `background_opacity` — scoped to kitty by
# definition, not Hyprland's global decoration.opacity. It applies to every
# kitty instance, so both plain terminals (Super+Q) and the yazi file-manager
# window (kitty --class=yazi) get it; other apps stay opaque.

# 0.0 = fully transparent, 1.0 = fully opaque. Per-theme knob — the key is
# still named `foot_alpha` (it predates kitty); both terminals read the one
# value, so they stay visually identical.
background_opacity {{foot_alpha}}

# Background AND foreground follow the palette; the ANSI 0–15 colours stay
# kitty's defaults for now (a full 16-colour per-theme terminal is future work).
# Theming the foreground is what makes a LIGHT palette usable — e.g.
# white-brown's cream background needs dark text here, or kitty's default light
# text would be unreadable. kitty wants '#'-prefixed hex; the palette stores bare.
background #{{background}}
foreground #{{foreground}}

# No font is set on purpose: kitty's default monospace is whatever fontconfig
# resolves, same as foot. Tune `font_family` / `font_size` here once judged on
# real hardware — it's an aesthetic call, not a generated one.
